<h2 id="airborne-pallet-tracker-app">Airborne Pallet Tracker App</h2>
<div class="media-Appicons-&amp;-description">
  <div class="icon-container">
    <a href="https://github.com/Richard-Burd/front-end-portfolio-project" target="_blank">
      <img class="github-icon" src="/img/misc/github.svg" alt="" />
    </a>

    <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CoZzR6K59Gg" target="_blank">
      <img class="youtube-icon" src="/img/misc/youtube.svg" alt="" />
    </a>
  </div>
  <p class="description">This single page application was built in pure JavaScript per assignment specifications and allows users to keep track of airborne shipping pallets</p>
</div>

<p>The Airborne Pallet Tracker application was designed to help military &amp; humanitarian logisticians keep track of airborne shipping pallets by color coating priority and weight classifications.Â   The user can keep track of how much space they have left in their storage areas, and decide which pallets have the highest priority to ship on the next available aircraft.</p>

<p><img src="https://i.imgur.com/4rNG98t.jpg" alt="app callouts &amp; UX/UI design" /></p>

<p>In order to reinforce fundamentals, this project had to be built in JavaScript alone <em>sans</em> any library or framework.Â   This led me to develop something I call the <a href="https://github.com/Richard-Burd/front-end-portfolio-project/blob/master/README.md#this-is-pure-javascript-by-design">builder-method</a> in order to organize the massive amount of JavaScript code that was required.Â   The back-end of this application utilizes a <a href="https://github.com/rails-api/rails-api">Rails API</a> that is shown below on the left in the light-green boxes.Â   The JavaScript front-end is shown below on the right in the light-blue boxes.</p>

<p><a href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1NrvuzRWSfcoiCbybQw29HBd4O9ObTcpo/view?usp=sharing" target="_blank">
<img src="https://i.imgur.com/28nI5ly.jpg" alt="schematic software diagram" />
</a></p>

